You may not use any other third-party libraries.

Looking at the mutation, the change is in the `invert` method:

Original: `} else if (op.retain && op.attributes) {`
Mutated: `} else if (true) {`

This is inside a `forEach` loop where we're processing `baseOp`s when `op.delete` is true. In the original code, when `op.delete` is truthy, it executes `inverted.insert(baseOp)` (the code before the `<PLACEHOLDER>`). The `else if` branch handles the case when `op.retain && op.attributes`.

Wait, let me re-read. The `<PLACEHOLDER>` IS the content of the `if (op.delete)` block. So:

Original:
```
if (op.delete) {
  // PLACEHOLDER = inverted.insert(baseOp)
} else if (op.retain && op.attributes) {
  inverted.retain(...)
}
```

Mutated:
```
if (op.delete) {
  // PLACEHOLDER = true (condition changed to always true)
} else if (true) {
  inverted.retain(...)
}
```

Wait, the placeholder IS the `else if` condition. So the original has `else if (op.retain && op.attributes)` and the mutated has `else if (true)`.

This means in the mutated version, when `op.delete` is false (i.e., when we have a retain with attributes), the `else if (true)` always executes `inverted.retain(...)`. But in the original, it only executes when `op.retain && op.attributes`.

Actually, looking more carefully - the mutation changes the condition from `op.retain && op.attributes` to `true`. This would affect cases where `op.retain` exists but `op.attributes` is null/undefined. In the original, if `op.retain` has no attributes, the `else if` block is skipped. In the mutated version, it always executes.

Let me write a test that inverts a delta where `op.retain` has no attributes - in the original, nothing happens for that case, but in the mutated version, `inverted.retain(Op.length(baseOp), AttributeMap.invert(undefined, baseOp.attributes))` would be called.

```typescript
import Delta from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/delta/src/Delta.ts";

describe('Delta invert', () => {
  it('should correctly invert a delete operation without adding spurious retains for retain ops without attributes', () => {
    // Create a base document: "hello world"
    const base = new Delta().insert('hello world');

    // Create a delta that retains 5 chars (no attributes) then deletes 6 chars
    const delta = new Delta().retain(5).delete(6);

    // The inverted delta should re-insert the deleted content
    const inverted = delta.invert(base);

    // Apply delta to base, then apply inverted to get back to base
    const applied = base.compose(delta);
    const restored = applied.compose(inverted);

    // The restored document should equal the original base
    expect(restored).toEqual(base);

    // Also check the inverted delta structure directly
    // It should be: retain(5), insert(' world')
    expect(inverted.ops).toEqual([
      { retain: 5 },
      { insert: ' world' }
    ]);
  });
});
```

Wait, the retain(5) with no attributes - in the original code, `typeof op.retain === 'number' && op.attributes == null` branch handles it (returns early with `inverted.retain(op.retain)`). So the `else if` branch wouldn't even be reached for that case. Let me reconsider what case would trigger the `else if` branch with the mutation.

The `else if` is reached when `op.delete` is falsy AND `op.retain` is a number but has attributes. With mutation `else if (true)`, it would also execute when `op.retain` is a number but has NO attributes... but that case is already handled above.

```typescript
